# CSS Flexbox üí™

The Flexible Box Layout Module makes it easier to design flexible responsive layout structure without using float or positioning.

## The Container
To start, set `display: flex;` on the parent container.

```css
.flex-container {
  display: flex;
}
```
Direct children become **flex items**.

# Flex Direction ‚û°Ô∏è

Defines the direction flex items are placed.

- `row` (default): Horizontal left-to-right.
- `row-reverse`: Horizontal right-to-left.
- `column`: Vertical top-to-bottom.
- `column-reverse`: Vertical bottom-to-top.

```css
.flex-container {
  display: flex;
  flex-direction: column;
}
```

# Align Items (Cross Axis) ‚ÜïÔ∏è

Aligns items along the cross axis (usually vertical).

- `stretch` (default): Stretch to fill container.
- `flex-start`: Top.
- `flex-end`: Bottom.
- `center`: Center.
- `baseline`: Align baselines.

```css
.flex-container {
  height: 200px;
  align-items: center;
}
```

# CSS Grid Layout üèÅ

Grid is a **2-dimensional** layout system (rows AND columns).

## The Container

```css
.grid-container {
  display: grid;
  grid-template-columns: auto auto auto;
  gap: 10px;
}
```

This creates a grid with 3 equal columns.

# Defining Columns & Rows üìè

Use `grid-template-columns` and `grid-template-rows` to define size.

## The `fr` Unit
The `fr` unit represents a fraction of available space.

```css
.grid-container {
  display: grid;
  grid-template-columns: 1fr 2fr 1fr;
}
```
(Middle column is twice as wide as others.)

## Repeat Function
`grid-template-columns: repeat(3, 1fr);` (Same as 1fr 1fr 1fr)

# Grid Template Areas üó∫Ô∏è

Named grid areas make layout code readable.

**Item:**
```css
.item1 { grid-area: header; }
.item2 { grid-area: menu; }
.item3 { grid-area: main; }
.item4 { grid-area: right; }
.item5 { grid-area: footer; }
```

**Container:**
```css
.grid-container {
  grid-template-areas:
    'header header header header header'
    'menu main main main right'
    'menu footer footer footer footer';
}
```
